00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:28.670
OK So inflation was a theory
for the very early universe

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:33.520
proposed by Alan Guth
and others In 1981.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:36.360
Alan Guth is a professor at MIT.

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:40.530
And this theory, that goes
under the name by inflation,

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:42.570
is the main paradigm
that explains

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:47.830
the observed inhomogeneities
in the universe today.

00:18:47.830 --> 00:18:50.970
Inflation is a period and
of accelerated expansion

00:18:50.970 --> 00:18:55.190
in the first fraction of the
second after the Big Bang.

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:58.920
And it explains why the universe
is approximately homogeneous

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:00.410
and spatially flat.

00:19:00.410 --> 00:19:04.360
We had several problems
before the theory of Inflation

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:05.670
was proposed.

00:19:05.670 --> 00:19:08.180
The problems were related
to why the universe is

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:14.910
observed to be so flat, why the
universe is observed to be so

00:19:14.910 --> 00:19:17.760
homogeneous at very
different scales

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:21.030
so this theory came into place.

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:25.180
It was proposed as a
solution for these problems.

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:28.350
So in the simplest
model of inflation,

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:31.750
there is a single scaler
field-- and by scaler field

00:19:31.750 --> 00:19:35.660
I mean a field that
takes different values

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:41.560
in different positions-- and
more common-- and more common

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:44.240
scaler field that we are
very used to it this,

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:45.781
for example, the temperature.

00:19:45.781 --> 00:19:46.280
OK?

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:47.280
That's a scalar field.

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:51.200
So the field takes different
values at different positions.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:53.020
So in that simplest
models of inflation,

00:19:53.020 --> 00:20:00.120
there is single scaler field
slowly rolling down a potential

00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:04.010
This scaler field is known
as the inflect on field.

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:08.360
So while it rolls
down the potential--

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:13.490
while it rolls of down the
potential-- different modes,

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:17.580
different perturbations
in this field

00:20:17.580 --> 00:20:20.210
stop being in constant contact.

00:20:20.210 --> 00:20:21.950
When they stop being
in constant contact,

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:25.630
and by this I mean that they
cannot exchange information

00:20:25.630 --> 00:20:31.150
with each other--
a perturbation--

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:33.910
an initial seed is frozen.

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:34.590
OK?

00:20:34.590 --> 00:20:39.140
And this initial seed is
what then gives rise to CMB

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:41.670
fluctuations that
we observe today.

00:20:41.670 --> 00:20:46.730
OK so the square amplitude
of this initial seed,

00:20:46.730 --> 00:20:51.960
I will call it the primordial
power spectrum-- which

00:20:51.960 --> 00:20:56.160
is the square amplitude of this
initial seed that gives rise

00:20:56.160 --> 00:21:01.650
to the observed CMB fluctuations
and the observed large-scale

00:21:01.650 --> 00:21:03.820
structure of the universe.

00:21:03.820 --> 00:21:09.970
So the idea is that the
field during inflation

00:21:09.970 --> 00:21:13.770
takes different values, and
these different values are

00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:17.650
associated with the
CMB fluctuations

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:21.220
at different angular
scales in the sky.

00:21:21.220 --> 00:21:24.370
So the idea is that by
looking at different angular

00:21:24.370 --> 00:21:27.950
scales in this guy
the CMB power spectrum

00:21:27.950 --> 00:21:35.020
